deck_excerpt: You thought you were safe from the fusion horror, now comes the red knights!
deck_description:
Hi everyone this deck is made with the release of Photon Hypernova set. I won't talk much about the old tearlaments cards so we will jump straight to the Kashtria in the decks...

Kashtria Part
1. Kashtria Unicorn - a good starter to hammer the extra deck and a primary searcher for the Kashtira Papiyas
2. Kashtria Fenrir - by default he was meant for utility but now SERVES a bigger purpose, he will help you search any of the Kashtria monsters in the deck (aim for Kashtria Tearlaments for fusion start or aim for Riseheart for XYZ start)
3. Tearlaments Kashtria - her name alone is treated as a Tearlaments card, with that Chaetcaros can search for her, Reinoheart can dump her, Kaleidoheart also can do the same. She's the new starter for Tearlaments and easiest to summon due to banish either 1 Kashtria card or Tearlaments cards then select whose top 3 of the deck to mill and should she be sent to GY, she'll mill another 2 on top of yours
4. Kashtria Riseheart - Alright this guy alone is a double edged sword on so many levels in this deck, should you activate his effect first, you can no longer fusion that turn but if you sequence it correctly, you can use him + any Kashtria to make Shangrila which is HARD to be destroyed and will acts as a starter to bring out Arisheart
5. Prime Planet Paraisos - without a doubt this card is Kashtria version of Ruined Realm Perleino BUT for every different attribute u gain 100 atk and IT'S NOT BOUND to your side of the field but BOTH you and your opponent. With Shangrila on the field expect to destroy 1 card each time you banish a card. You can use it to search any kashtria to start the madness
6. Kashtira Papiyas - this magic spell is a recycler for your Kashtria cards that is banished by Ariseheart. Not only it serves as a free summon of a different attribute, it acts as a permanent material for ariseheart effect spam

7. Kashtria Shangri-la - This is not the boss but just an Ant Queen, pouring her army to the field at every standby phase both you and your opponent. The biggest catch is it's indestructability as long as it has a material or as long as its effect is not negated.
8. Kashtria Ariseheart - by the time this guy is out, the whole field is swarmed with both tearlaments and Kashtria monsters, nothing goes to the GY anymore, it's just instant banish after banish with Shangri-la locking parts of the field for every banish once per turn

Tearlaments
1. Tearlaments Perlegia - This will act as a permanent fusion plant for you as long as you can cycle 1 Aqua monster to the GY each time by the effect of your own Tearlaments or opponents card effects

Based on playtesting, you can takeout Winda & Shadoll Beast and replace them with another Shangri-la or Lulucaros with Kashtria Big Bang in the main deck to maximize the damage of these enemies clad in red can do with your fusions

deck_name: Very Bad Deck Don’t Use This
deck_description:
Hello! Please don't use this deck! We are, in short, a beginner. In long, we used to play a yugioh game on the ds from before they even added synchros (practically goat format) and have only very recently started playing Master Duel. This is our first deck in that game! It got us to gold 3 and taught us A LOT about how the game works now. Plus, it's fun, so big success all around.

We decided it'd be fun to keep track of the decks we make and write a little about them, like this. It gives us an opportunity to think and share and receive criticism; although, we're not really looking for criticism on this deck specifically. We have a Weather Painters deck in the works so be excited >:3

The deck was designed to, hopefully, get out Red-Eyes Flare Metal Dragon as much as possible, because I thought it was cool. More than that, people in low ranks don't know how to play around the protection or will get themselves so low that the other sources of burn can easily win the game. We can get a Red-Eyes Flare Metal Dragon with most hands and if not, it can usually get Meteor Black Comet Dragon and put out a lot of face damage with Inferno Fire Blast. We can FTK like that but in most cases it at least does a pretty good job seeding the GY.

We didn't really know what we were doing with the extra deck, especially with link monsters. (You can't blame us for that!) Borreload Savage Dragon usually only gets 1 negate with Striker Dragon but hey, sometimes that's enough.

We'll definitely improve on this deck sometime later down the line since there are only so many cards we can get our hands on and these ones are nice. At any rate, I hope you enjoyed this for what it is =w=

deck_description:
UPDATE: Now that Toadally Awesome is banned I've changed up the extra deck a bit.

Umi now has a clear win condition thanks to Ocean Dragon Lord - Kairyu-Shin, a monster that floodgates non-Water decks as long as you have Umi or a card that acts like Umi on the field. In order to set this up we run 13 cards to get to Umi: 3 A Legendary Ocean, 3 Ocean Dragon Lord - Kairyu-Shin (Which can also search spells and traps? What a crazy card!), 3 Warrior of Atlantis, 3 Sea Stealth II and 1 Terraforming; and 10 cards to get to Kairyu-Shin: 3 copies of itself, 3 Fish Sonar and 3 Electric Jellyfish, this last card, Electric Jellyfish, is specially great because it's effect to negate can protect Kairyu-Shin searching for Sea Stealth Attack (To then protect your Umi and keep Kairyu-Shin's lock alive) from Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring or Effect Veiler. It's also worth noting the Pot cards for extra consistency, no discretion needed when activating these as we don't really use the extra deck outside of the eventual Bahamut Shark into Toadally Awesome when we are ahead. Lastly, we run a Fury of Kairyu-Shin/Torrential Tribute package that fits the theme of the deck really well.

deck_excerpt: Can the forces of Light and Dark work together?
deck_description:
With Tear being one of the best deck, quickly followed by runick spright, this deck aims to make use of a variety of archtypes to drown your opponent in resources and drain their GY of monsters.

This deck is an amalgamation of 3 archtypes: Byssted, Dogmatika, and various chaos monsters(with shaddoll in as a spicy tech.). The new Byssted monsters came out in darkwing blast and they are strong. Lubellion is the searcher but the rest of the Byssted monsters can be special summoned from the hand by banishing a light or dark from either GY, and this is a quick eff if the opponent controls a monsters, so they are d.d. crows at times. And each has a unique effect that activates when special summoned or sent to the GY. Magmahut searches at end phase, druiswurm targeting sends a special summoned monster your opponent controls to the GY, and Saronir sends a Byssted monster or Branded spell/trap. They also have a boss monster in Alba Los but he can be very matchup dependet and requires a lot to get out so hes best in the side deck since he's pretty searchable with lubellion and chaos space that if you know he's game winning, you can make him. 

The dogmatika package is something we are all pretty familiar with by now but this time around those sends off nadir servent actually mean more than just a free pop. They also represent a light or dark in the GY to be banished for the Byssted monsters opening up a real use for maximus.The Dogmatika monsters are also all lights, which means once they hit the GY they still have use. 

The chaos monsters are an inclusion of my own choice. Chaos space is basically always live in your oppener by searching either lubellion or one of the chaos monsters, as well as being prime ash bait for your gamma to intercept. Psy-frame gamma are also excellent in this build cause of all the must negates(nadir, chaos space, lubellion) and they can be used as fodder to go into the GY for your Byssted monsters. 

I have had so much fun with this deck. The format right now is flooded with tear, branded, albaz, mathmech, and even spright play a good number of light and darks. The only real downside for this deck right now is it's price so I would suggest playing this mostly on Online servers like Dueling book and Omega.

All of the human Dragonmaids are Level 3 or below with the exception of Chamber Dragonmaid, which means they can be equipped to the Cyberdark monsters as equip spell cards from the GY.....thats literally all of the thought process put into here lol. Just a fun mash-up of cards. Hope ya'll get a kick out of it. 

As for some of the plays you can make with this...you really just wanna get your Dragonmaids in the GY so they can be equipped to your Cyberdarks. There are plenty of spell cards here that allow you to special summon Dragonmaids as well as cards that allow you to gain additional normal summons of Cyberdarks. Use these to go into Fusions or Link summons in order to set up your GY and then bring out the Cyberdarks to equip them with the Dragonmaids. 

Striker Dragon is just in here as another way to get Dragonmaids into the GY. No use for it's effect in this deck.
2 CARD COMBO TO SUMMON 5 STARDUST BOSS MONSTERS

A personal build of Labrynths, inspired by many of the decks here and on social media. Shout out to Eva Lees on Twitter for some of the ideas. Now for card choices. I will skip the more obvious cards.

Main deck:

2x Lady Labrynth of the Silver Castle - definitely the star of the deck and tends to win games by itself against decks that can't out her with you interrupting their plays. I don't play 3x because drawing two, especially in the opening hand, doesn't help you start your engine any faster, and you search her out either way. Use Arianna to fetch her, then Special Summon her. 

1x Ariane the Labrynth Servant - decent as a one-of, in case you need an easy Abyss Dweller/Number 41: Bagooska the Terribly Tired Tapir or to push your engine into over-drive with you drawing two cards every turn with her and Arianna the Labrynth Servant's effect. Can be used to start the engine in case of a bad draw or after having the entire board cleared, but unfortunately contests the same normal Summon as her green counterpart.

2x Lord of the Heavenly Prison - after being hit by one-too-many Feather Dusters, I learned to love this card. It protects your back row from most of the common ways your opponents will try to deal with it (with the exception of Cosmic Cyclone) and you can even get a big dumb beater! Of course, his best use is to enable your plays by setting Welcome Labrynth or any other high-value trap, like Dogmatika Punishment. 

2x Archfiend's Ghastly Glitch - use it to dump, then revive Arianna, Lady or Lovely Labrynth of the Silver Castle if you have the field spell, or Labrynth Chandraglier/Labrynth Stovie Torbie if you don't, so you could get it later. Can also be used to dump Absolute King Back Jack for a surprise Trap out of nowhere!

2x Terrors of the Overroot - a very overlooked card, it triggers the effects of Lovely Labrynth and the Servants while also interrupting GY plays. In many matchups it's fantastic and in those where GY effects aren't used that often you can still set a monster that was used as material or was destroyed by your other cards and just run over it with one of your many surprisingly-high ATK monsters.

Extra deck:

1-3x Number 41: Bagooska the Terribly Tired Tapir - a sleeper hit, it's a fiend, which means it can be revived in the middle of your opponents turn by Labrynth Labyrinth, seriously screwing up their plays.Consider playing multiple if you're afraid of banishing them with Pot of Extravagance.

1x Five-Headed Link Dragon - while primarily acting as a Dogmatika Punishment target if you really need to get rid of something with more than 3000 ATK, you can, hilariously enough, summon it with the help of Stovie Torbie, Ariane and Welcome Labrynths. It's a very silly towers-like card and shouldn't be taken too seriously.

1x Muckraker From the Underworld - unlike Beat Cop from the Underworld, who protects your field spell, Muckraker isn't used much for protection, as Lady Labrynth of the Silver Castle can't be destroyed by card effects anyway and Muckraker's 1000 ATK will just mean she's the first target for any battle. She's here for her amazing revive effect, allowing you to recycle Arianna, or get either Lady or Lovely back, in case you're missing your field spell. 

Side deck:

Like always, play whatever fits the metagame you're trying to beat. Additional choices to consider are going second cards like Evenly Matched and Lightning Storm. Cards like Dimension Shifter and There Can Be Only One hurt you too, but they hurt some meta decks far worse. TCBOO in particular can create a situation where your opponent simply can't out Lady Labrynth with just a single archetypal monster on the field, while she keeps setting traps and beating over guys every turn.

deck_description: I got this decklist from DarkArmedDuelist and wanted to have a physical list so I didn't have to keep going back to the video. Side deck and extra deck seems to be format dependent so if you see this list in a few years, change the ghost girls to what the meta specifically revolves around and change the extra deck to Super Poly targets.

Hey Cimoooooooo and/or MonoBlueTron, you and one of your yugitubing co-creators should make a new series about the many different archetypes that are in the card game. The History of Yugioh! Series and The History of Jank Series only shows the historical archetypes that were "competitively viable". HOWEVER, there are many more archetypes that have been overlooked. People that watch your channels may only know the names of each archetype, but they may not know how each archetype plays. For example, Gravekeeper's are too slow for the current meta, but are fun and have an interesting playstyle. For this series, you should:

1) Show a unique archetype - the archetype must be the main focus of the deck, no archetypes that have not many names (e.g. Malicevorous)

2) Show a playstyle - some archetypes can have different playstyles depending on the cards being played in the deck (e.g. HERO decks can vary in playstyles depending on what is in the main and extra deck)

3) Use the most recent banlist and card pool - Darkwing Blast just released support for the Blackwing and Amazoness archetypes and yet, neither archetype will be the next SPYRAL deck

In any case, I plan to show off more of these type of decks such as this one.
Stops them in their tracks

deck_excerpt: Bet you never expected this, did you?
deck_description: Now, your first question may be: Why the hell are you combining Runick with Phantom Knights? well, why combine Runick with Spright? It´s because Hugin is a level 2 which enables all your Spright plays. In Runick Phantom Knigt, it´s the same principle, only worse. Munin the Runick Wings is a level 3, and because cherubini requires any 2 level 3s to make, any Runick quick-play + level 3 monster can lead to nearly a full Phantom Knight combo. The Runick engine does more than just this, obviously. You also get a ton of interruptions if your combo starts to go south, and Fountain being the broken card it is, allows for drawing 3 for that grind game.

deck_excerpt: What was once yours is now mine
deck_description: Control
hyyh
Gimini

The main deck combo goes as follows:
sunseed loci
l1 Dryas
retrieve sunvinesowing
summon sunseed twin
summon from gy loci
summon healer

from here, you can proceed into an OTK combo if the enemies board is open
take all 3, go into the link 3 sunavalon monster
sunseed from gy
sunseed into l1 thrasher
thrasher target effect sunavalon l3 (this makes his attack 3.2k)
sunavalon target the sunvine thrasher, this allows for 2 attacks this turn (6.4k)
take the sunavalons and turn them into a bengahlancer for a 2.5k beatstick with the ability to quick effect bounce (mainphase)
bear in mind, that the sunvine thrasher can summon a monster that it sends to the gy to the zone bengalancer points to, so if you beat an enemy with 3k attack that's an additional 3k *and* you steal it from their gy.

Moving on, the rest of the normal combo
heal yourself with sunvine healer as she gets special summoned
make jasmine l2 and tribute a monster she points too
summon generaider from the deck
use generaider to search for the aromage l1
special summon aromage l1
use the aromage and the generaider to make a 2nd l2 jasmine
pop aromage's effect to pop jasmine's effect, this activates both of their affects
search rikka lvl 8 and rikka lvl 6
make with the l2 that's not in the extra deck zone and the sunseed loci, the l3 avalon monster
l3 summons the loci back
make another l3 with the avalon card
summon loci back from the gy again
then proceed to summon Dryas and use his effect again to bring from your deck your sunvine shrine
tribute the dryas for lvl 6 rikka, give yourself the rikka glamour
use glamor and tribute the lvl 6, give yourself the lvl 4 rikka primula and you have two options, either carrotweight or rikka princess (if you have the field spell give yourself the rikka, otherwise it's up to your decision)
summon the rikka primula since you tributed the other rikka
special summon rikka princess
or
activate the sunvine shrine and send carrot to the gy, summon him by sending someone from your hand to the gy
make rikka strenna
strenna, target a plant monster in the gy, preferably lonefire blossom
use the other rikka lvl 8 to special summon (tribute the strenna) her and another plant monster (any)
tributing the strenna allows you to special summon and attach the strenna to sacred tree beast
from here, you can make benghalancer, then make l4 sunavalon off of begnhalancer, then revive begnhalancer making the l4 allows you to draw the trap card
use the lvl 8 rikka and whatever you special summoned to make a teardrop
activate the shrine, special summon a loci, and link him into a thrasher, target the l4 sunavalon for a 4k attack thrasher
this procs sacred tree beast to allow you to attach a spell from the gy to him 

congrats, you have:
1 quick effect tribute
1 quick effect monster or spell negate
1 quick effect bounce
1 trap card negate all on field (not your monsters though) this trap also effects l4 monsters in damage calculation, adding the attack of all the monsters they point to
1 quick effect negate (potentially even tributing your enemies monster if the field spell is on the field)

and in some iterations of the combo, a spell and trap stun that allows only 1 spell/trap to activate per turn on the enemy. 

You can use rivalary as a floodgate in this as well

Rikka Sheet is a funny prevent from activating effects, so if they normal summon something that doesn't say "quick effect" or "when normal summoned" you can slap that on them and go "stop that" theoretically works on accesscode talker to prevent him from using his destructions. Or you can tribute someone and steal their monster for extra fuckery.

This deck aims to use the new Umi support in tandem with some powerful floodgates to control the board and win games!

I am using The Legendary Fisherman II and III as II is pretty strong on its own, being unaffected by other monster effects, but III is nearly impossible to out, banishes the opponents whole board and is huge to boot!

I am using 3 soul drain as I think its required going into a pure Tearlament meta.

I am using 3 TCBOO as your usual end board you want is Kairyu-Shin, Electric Jellyfish and Mega Fortress Whale which are all different types so TCBOO doesn't affect you in most circumstances.

Giga Gagagigo is the largest level 5 WATER Normal monster you can play, the next best option you can play is Frostisaurus which is level 6 but has 150 more attack (it rarely ever comes up so sticking with Giga Gagagigo is best)

deck_excerpt: Level 4 monsters ("Adin", "Ecclesia", and "Theo") share the following effects: "Cannot be destroyed by battle with a monster Special Summone
deck_description:
Level 4 monsters ("Adin", "Ecclesia", and "Theo") share the following effects: "Cannot be destroyed by battle with a monster Special Summoned from the Extra Deck. You can only use each of the following effects of "[this card]" once per turn." and "If a monster that was Special Summoned from the Extra Deck is on the field: You can Special Summon this card from your hand." This allows them to quickly invade the field and enter Rank 4 Xyz Monsters. Examples of good generic Rank 4s include "Number S39 Utopia Supreme", "Daigusto Emeral", "Cowboy Gagaga", etc.

 

"Fleurdelis Dogmatik, the Knightly Army" also features a similar Summon condition and supports "Dogmatik" monsters by making them gain ATK whenever a "Dogmatik" monster declares an attack, allowing for quick victory when combined with the provided swarm. by lower Level monsters. Because its Summon condition is a Quick Effect, it can be Summoned during the opponent's turn to interrupt their game, negating the effects of one of their monsters.

 

"Maximus Dogmatik" and "Nexus Dogmatik" benefit from Extra Deck monsters in the Graveyard since their Summon condition involves banishing an Extra Deck monster from the Graveyard. Accumulating Extra Deck monsters is achieved with their support Spell and Trap Cards, but also with "Maximus", sending cards from the Extra Deck to the Graveyard. Because of this, it is recommended that Extra Deck monsters have effects while they are in the Graveyard. Monsters that have a decent Attribute and Type range make "Archimemeses Eschatos" and "Archimemeses Protos" good optional "boss monsters" in the Deck. "Zaborg the Mega Monarch" can also help set up the Graveyard. Since "Nexus" can be Summoned multiple times per turn, this card makes getting multiple copies of it very easy.

 

Due to its heavy reliance on monsters Summoned from the Extra Deck being on the field and its own inability to Summon them regularly, it is an archetype focused on going second. The opponent who does not Summon a monster from the Extra Deck can also damage the Deck. To make up for this weakness, it is recommended to have a few copies of "Instant Fusion" to easily Summon monsters from the Extra Deck (care should be taken when playing "Dogmatik Punishment", "Ecclesia Dogmatik, the Virtuous", "Maximus Dogmatik" and/or or "Servant Nadir"; as it can throw off one's own strategy if not timed correctly). If "Thousand-Eyes Limit" or "Thousand-Eyes Limit" is Summoned in this way, they can be used to Link Summon "Linkuriboh", instantly giving him a material to Summon "Maximus" and with the help of The invoked leaves cards like mechaba and more useful cards and use all the power of the new card White Zoa of Dogmatika

deck_excerpt: Tearlament and Ishizu cards get you down with their obnoxious GY effects? Necrovalley Dragoon is the anti-meta deck for you! NO GY ALLOWED!
deck_description:
Necrovalley has been an anti-meta staple since it's inception since it effectively locks down the graveyard. This singular card has slaughtered nearly every deck rogue and meta deck throughout the different eras of competitive Yugioh - Dragon Ruler, Spellbook, Kozmo, Orcust, Sky Striker, Thunder Dragon, Spyral - and more recently, Necrovalley is primed to take on Spright, Ishizu and Tearlaments. 

Dragoon is also a force of nature on it's own - untargetable, indestructible, 3000ATK, omni-negate, it can increase it's own attack and burn up to twice per turn! Dragoon is a ridiculously powerful card, and getting it out is extremely easy as well with Red-Eyes Fusion being easily accessible. The only downside is that Red-Eyes Fusion prevents any summoning for an entire turn, which seriously prevents Dragoon from being usuable in many decks. Not that it is a problem for Necrovalley, since all the cards do is slap down the incredibly powerful field spell!

 

Necrovalley paired up with some Konami employee's ridiculous "DeviantArt-OC" Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon, Necrovalley is nigh-unstoppable!

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

 

ARCHETYPES, ENGINES AND DECKBUILDING

 

  • Forming the deck’s core, The Necrovalley cards in the Main Deck consist of 10 cards:

3 Necrovalley, 1 Necrovalley Throne, 3 Gravekeeper's Commandant, and 1 Terraforming. This gives you 10 copies of the field spell, almost guaranteeing that you'll see it in your opening hand. 

  • The Dragoon cards in the maindeck consists of 9 cards:

1 Dark Magician, 1 Red-Eyes Black Dragoon, 1 Red-Eyes Wyvern, 3 Red-Eyes Insight and 3 Red-Eyes Fusion. In the Extra Deck, there are 3 Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon. These cards enable arguably one of the most ridiculous cards ever printed by Konami - Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon.

  • Generic Support cards assist the strategy and consist of 10 cards.

3 Pot of Prosperity, 1 Called by the Grave, 3 Inspector Boarder and 3 Scapegoat. Inspector Boarder is another stun staple, and gives the deck an additional normal summon/set. Scapegoat can be set, and be used at your opponent's end phase to generate 4 tokens. During your turn, you can use the tokens to make the Link-4 boss monster of choice!

  • Board Breaker and Staple Handtraps cards consist of 15 cards.

3 Dark Ruler No More, 3 Evenly Matched, 3 Super Polymerization, 3 Infinite Impermance and 3 Dimension Shifter. These cards can singlehandedly turn the odds in your favour with their devastating board breaking/turn ending potential.

43 cards are used in this deck to lower the possibility of drawing into bricks/garnets like Dark Magician, Red-Eyes Black Dragon, and Red-Eyes Wyvern.

If you're missing a piece of your strategy, missing cards can be easily accessed through Pot of Prosperity. Prosperity is easily used in this deck, since not every Extra Deck monster is needed. However, be careful about banishing your Super Poly/Scapegoat monsters!

COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN

 

Necrovalley Dragoon is fairly easy to play, since it doesn't involve multiple combo routes, complex decision making and resource management. Functioning as an anti-meta stun deck, you simply lockdown your opponent with a combination of Necrovalley and Dragoon until your opponent concedes or loses!

Able to go first or second thanks to the wide variety of devastating board breakers and crippling handtraps, Necrovalley Dragoon can play either way. Preferably going first is best, since it allows the player to initiate their stun set-up as soon as possible.

Going first, the gameplan is pretty simple - try to summon Dragoon and set up Necrovalley. Use your Dragoon's omni-negate wisely! 

Going second, boards are broken with a combination of Dragoon + Dark Ruler No More/Evenly Matched. If you are missing a certain card to break your opponent's board, try to dig for it with Pot of Prosperity. After Dragoon is successfully on board, it is a nigh unstoppable juggernaut, capable of destroying two monsters with it's effect and running over another monster in the battle phase. After Dragoon's onslaught, you "checkmate" your opponent with Necrovalley so they cannot access their graveyard for any play or resources. 

Your win condition is Dragoon and Necrovalley. If either of those come out, it is often game over for your opponent, especially if they're playing a GY-reliant deck like Tearlaments, Branded or Mathmech.

 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

 

GENERAL TIPS

  • Use Dragoon's omni-negate wisely! Think about the "outs" your opponent has to Necrovalley/Dragoon, and save your precious omni-negate for that. 
  • If you already have all the pieces of your gameplan in your hand, use Pot of Prosperity after you thin out your deck so you have the highest chance to get the card you want.
  • If you notice that your opponent barfs out all their resources on their first turn board and lose instantly to Necrovalley, let them go first. Going second, blow up their board, set up Necrovalley, and checkmate your opponent for the win!
  • Scapegoat can be set and used at your opponent's end phase to generate 4 tokens. During your turn, you can use the tokens to make the Link-4 boss monster of choice! Hint: Avramax backed by I:P Masquereena is an instant win vs. some decks. 
 

CONCLUDING COMMENTARY

Tired of all these GY reliant decks using the GY as their second hand and popping off? Tired of the endless milling and chains that meta decks like Ishizu Tearlaments, Branded and Mathmech do when they start their combo? NECROVALLEY DRAGOON IS PERFECT FOR YOU!!!

No more GY effects, no more GY banishing, no more GY shuffling. Monsters, spells and traps can finally rest and be at peace...

If you recently pulled or obtained your Dragoons, Pot of Prosperities and Dimension Shifters just like me from the 2022 Tins, Necrovalley Dragoon is the perfect deck to use them in!

My personal take on the Runick/Mysterune archeytype.

It's a very straightforward deck, You are a player/mage/spellcaster/first person character in a world of duel monsters, facing those monsters and their masters with your arsenal of spells and traps to combat them, disarm the opponent and Win. 

This archetype is so versatile that You can build it in countless ways and experiment with them to their full potential in Your hand. It can make You feel like a Professional or like a Novice, it's all about perspective and preference of cards. 

The Main Deck consists of 40 Main Deck Cards, of which are 37 Spells and 3 Traps, as we can see, it's a deck with 0 Main Deck monsters and that was the whole point of this build, among many other things. 15 Extra Deck Cards and 15 Side Deck Cards. 

The Main Deck consists mostly of Runick Cards, followed by Quick-Play supplements, bait and mind games. Runicks are made to disarm your opponent as you deplete their deck with every card you use, their secondary use is counter and control, as majority of those Runick Cards hit a card(s) on the field You or Your Opponent controls, forcing them to play carefully with every step they make, every breath they take, every card they'll be missing in the process. The Non-Runick Cards are there to help You control Your opponent's Monsters and keep them in check.


26.6% of the Extra Deck is summonable by 22-25 cards in the Main Deck, as every Quick-Play Runick Spell and Waking the Dragon can special summon any of the 4 Runick Fusions we currently have, beats having to use Instant Fusion anyday.

73.3% - 100% of the Extra Deck is summonable with Waking the Dragon, while it's a gamble if your opponent will truly attack your backrow, this deck all but guarantees You will get hit by a backrow wiping effect. If our opponent notices we're using Sky Striker Spells, filler Quick-Play Spells such as Forbidden Cards and the Book of Eclipse, we open up the mind game with them of "What could it be that's facedown?" causing them to have a sense of temptation to find out, which puts additional stress on their mind to focus on the match. All Extra Deck monsters handpicked as the best of the best, while it's true there are other candidates that also provide a coverage, these 11 were my own pick in the end. IF You're playing an OCG Version, simply replace Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon for Thunder Dragon Colossus.

The entire point of the Side Deck is to have a counter to cards that can be an issue to You as a Runick player, what better way than with a large Kaiju package, along with some backrow wipers and a few "One Card Solves All". You're playing Runick people hate when you have cards on your field, especially the Field which is perhaps your most important card in the match. That being said, you will fairly often find yourself with an empty field, that Evenly Match makes it so your opponent too feels the sting, slows them down immensely if their entire engine is field based.

It's Not a Perfect Deck, no such thing as a Perfect Deck, no such thing as a True Tier 0 deck, never has been, never will be, but this is a deck that can score You a victory when You least expect it, it can provide that unique sense and taste of fun and Victory, even satisfaction and a lesson in Loss.

Happy Dueling.
-T.B.

deck_excerpt: I promise this one's actually good, I trained for a million years with this deck list
deck_description:
A few days ago i uploaded a Bystial BA deck, and then after that, i tested it in ranked on YGO Omega and got my butt cheeks handed to me. This list at least got me a single game in ranked against a good Marincess deck (i'm ass at playing high-level Yugioh, its a skill issue), so it should fair better.

 

Basically, your immediate goals are to either make Dante or make your once per turn monster negate (Cicada King), set any traps in hand, and then preferably get out Rexterm on turn 2 so you can shut down your opponent's combo lines. If you can spam enough bodies on board, you can make Tri-Heart or Decode Talker. There's 3 Rexterm in the deck because Kshatri exists now, and once Arise-Heart comes out in the TCG, its gonna be really, REALLY annoying when your important extra deck cards get sent to the Shadow Realm on turn 1. You may adjust the side deck as necessary, but unless there's some techs i just don't know about (either that, or if Small World is just that good in this deck), idk if you'll need to mess with the main deck much.

 

I'll have a video out at some point later. If i can't edit this page when that's ready (the site bugs out sometimes), i'll have to delete and reupload this list.

deck_excerpt: Lockdown your opponent using traps to quickly build a board on their turn and push for game
deck_description:
Dinomorphia has one glaring weakness, paying lifepoints. even with some pretty busted effects, continually paying half your lifepoints puts you in a bad position when it comes to the timeclock. If a game is forced to time, you are basically guarenteed a loss because your lifepoints will always be lower at the end of whatever phase the game might be in outside of maybe your battle phase.

That being said. the name of the game is move fast. Shutdown your opponent in the first turn and push for game as soon as possible. going second is a challenge for this deck but not undoable. and when you do know your going second, the evenly matched cleans up nicely 

My favorite play is to prioritize getting at least 2 level 4's on the field at the start of your turn 2 using alert in the opponents end phase. xyz into raider's knight and raider's knight into Arc Rebellion. with usually at least a rextrum or two kentregina's on the field, Arc Rebellion gets HUGE and can swing over any attack position for game. Warning Point helps with this if you catch your opponents off guard when they summon something in attack position looking to use it for a special summon.

-AA ZEUS is a nice followup with all the xyz access this deck provides.

*Its important to note you should prioritize getting sonic in the grave as soon as possible or fusing off from the field to mitigate battle damage as Diplos/Therizia are easy targets to swing over if you have been paying lots of life.

-Recovering with this deck is sometimes hard because you dedicate all the gas in early game. Sometimes its best to scoop and get into the side deck if they shut down your board as it will be a race against time to secure game 3 and you can side in more effective traps for whatever matchup you face 

All in all I think this decks weakness is itself when it comes to competitive play. between the OP effects (like a walking skill drain in rex) and multitude of negates, winning isnt usually the issue. I find myself going to time more often then i like and getting handed a loss even when i have complete control of the board. Definatly my favorite rogue deck by far.

There is absolutely nothing better than pissing off meta decks playing a bunch of traps

deck_excerpt: A "Galaxy or Galactic" Deck focuses on Summoning various Level 8 monsters for Xyz Summons. By using "Accelerlight" to Special Summon a "Gala
deck_description:
A "Galaxy or Galactic" Deck focuses on Summoning various Level 8 monsters for Xyz Summons. By using "Accelerlight" to Special Summon a "Galaxy Wizard", its Level can be changed to 8, and by using "Galaxy Expedition" to bring out "Galaxy-Eyes Photon Dragon" to instantly Summon an Xyz Monster from Rank 8. "Galaxy Zero" can be used to revive a Level 8 monster, Normal Summon "Galaxy Knight", and revive "Galaxy-Eyes Photon Dragon" to attach them to "Galaxy-Eyes Neo Photon Dragon", "Number 107 Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon Dragon" or "Number 62 Prime Galaxy-Eyes Photon Dragon".

 

The effect of "Galaxy Wizard" can search for most of the important Spells and monsters in the Deck, but using its effect leaves your LP exposed. Because of this, it is recommended to use "Photon Thumper" to maintain presence on the field, with the added bonus that "Thunder" can be used with "Wizard" for Rank 4 Xyz Monsters like "Starlord Paladin" and "Constellation Omega". Also, the Special Summon of "Thunderer" allows you to Normal Summon "Galaxy Knight" without Tributing in the same turn.

 

The inclusion of "Galaxy Soldier" combined with "Galaxy Expedition" also gives the player the opportunity to incorporate some capable Rank 5 monsters, such as "Constellation Pleiades". An excellent combo is to discard a "Galaxy-Eyes" with "Soldier" to Summon the latter, then use the "Soldier" search effect to add a "Galaxy Knight" to the hand. "Galaxy Knight" can be Normal Summoned and revive "Galaxy-Eyes" in the Graveyard, to Special Summon a Rank 8 monster. "Soldier's" effect is sometimes used with other LIGHT archetypes, such as "Kozmo or "Artifact" to speed up powerful Rank 5 Xyz Summons like "Constellation Pleiades", "Cyber ​​Dragon Nova" to "Cyber ​​Dragon Infinity". While "Soldier" can be used on its own, a single "Wizard" can be used to search for "Galaxy Expedition" to Special Summon "Galaxy-Eyes Photon Dragon" or another "Soldier", depending on if it's a Rank 5 Xyz Summon or brute force is needed.

deck_excerpt: Win the duel in just one turn
deck_description:
Hello welcome to my Exodia deck profile,

 

as every other Exodia FTK deck you need to have royal magical library and get three counters on it. It is important to mention that you should search first then draw, so you don't draw into garnets like toon-world and spellbook of knowledge. In that case you need to shuffle them back in the deck with magical mallet. Searching also makes your deck thin, which means you get faster to your good cards. The bamboo engine is without a doubt very broken in this deck. Golden bamboo sword gives you free pluses. In my earlier builds I played pot of duality, but since I figured out that magicians souls can also pop the cursed bamboo swords to generate plus 4, I decided to play more special summon focused. With the new bamboo sword, you can equip a cursed bamboo sword directly from your deck so you can pop it with magicians souls, draw and then search another golden. It is very very broken until you find out. We play gold moon coin in this deck to give our remaining piri-reis map or librarys to our opponent to draw 2. Top share is also very good in this deck, topdecking what we want. 

I also played the endymion version with the og endymion and wonder wand loop. Personally I think it is less efficient and much less consistent but for sure funny. If you have any ideas how to optimize this deck even more, feel free to comment, thanks.

deck_excerpt: I've been playtesting Dream Mirror ever since it's release, and now that it's come to Master Duel I present my Masterpiece!
deck_description:
Ever since Dream Mirror came out it's been called one of the worst archetypes, and for good reason. It barely had an endboard, it was bricky as hell and barely had synergy with eachother.

Until we got Neiroy Traitor from Battle of Chaos. Since then I've been tinkering with different versions of this deck and in conclusion I've come up with my favorite and most powerful deck.

"But isn't this just Kali Yuga Turbo?" Yeah? so what? Screw you

What it comes down to is a 1 card combo with Neiroy searching Ikelos into Friend and into the Phantom Knight combo to search the Quick-Play Rank-up spell and getting Utopia Kaiser onto the field to bring out D/D/D Duo-Dawn King Kali Yuga on your opponents turn, actively shutting down their turn.

It's very consistent since it's a one card combo with one hard garnet. Luckily if you have Dream Mirror of Terror and Neiroy in hand you can tuck back those silly garnets like a Phantom Knight monster or Double-or-Nothing. And if you can't? You can end on a Redoer with trap material, 2 Fog Blades and Tormentor.

Unfortunately this deck can die to pretty much any handtrap in the game. Which is why we run Crossout and CBTG for obvious reasons!

"Why is there Jerry Beans Man in here?" He's a Small World bridge. He's the MVP in this deck, because almost any monster in this deck can bridge with Jerry Beans Man into Neiroy!

I've been clapping some serious cheeks with this deck. Of course it's not great in any capacity, but once you get the end board you basically win the game. I hope you enjoy playing my decklist!

deck_excerpt: vernalizer,vernusylph,magnet warrior,electromagnet warrior,adamancipator,adamatia,rock good stuff,good stuff
deck_description:
Video showcase vs all meta (32 Min video): https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IGajkxIStG8

First of all the deck is strong tier 2, Yet maybe 4-5 people worldwide know it exists.
Deck Notes: ADAMANCIPATORS at 2? * Vernusylphs are the primary way to turbo the deck and do a better job then them. Secondary consistency is nice but if included properly. * Both Researcher and Analyzer suck when Drawn at multiples or get excavated. * Analyzer also overlaps with 3 Fenrirs & Nibiru (You also side one out when siding more nibs, Bystials). * Researcher is also primary Gallant target so drawing him is a bit redundant. * Adamancipator Seeker wasn't good enough, altho 1 copy of it if you dont own / cant afford the consistency spells wont hurt. SEKKA & PROSP?? Wut? (Btw you can banish 6 with Prosp easily) If you could play 4 copies of prosperity or 4 copies of light of sekka would you do it? The answer should be yes. VERNU Ratio: Just 1 Vernusylph bunny? This deck doesn't fill up the GY as well as naturia monsters for example, you need an earth in GY to activate him Just 1 Vernusylph Winny the Po bear? I rated prosperity higher, if you cant afford prosperity max out on bears and reduce to 40. VERA needed? Each effect was relevant... Reviving Guardian, lvl 3 magnet warrior which set up 5 earths / IP, stealing monsters. Kinda needed due to type of removal. MY MAGNET WARRIOR RATIO: Essentially this ratio gives the engine enough durability to perform various search and swarm cycles from every root. If Anyone wants Berserkion ratio over Valkyrion ratio for Berserkion I ran: 3 Beta. 1 Alpha. 1 Gamma - sadly required (marauding captain one). 1 Delta - sadly nerfed as we dont have Berserkion. 2 Epsilon. 1 Berserkion. is barrier statue mandatory? Well I have had replays where I won summoning it going second, most meta decks summon at both turns. I mean the deck can turbo Gallant has both Adamancipators and Vernusylphs... Kinda hard not to run it. HOW TO STATUE LOCK: Statue + Hyper Psychic Riser (lvl 6 earth synchro, floodgates <2k monsters from atking, higher ones from activating effs). I Didnt like Riser enough. Statue + VW Jaya - makes it undestructable Statue + Bagooska - They cant run over statue Statue + Gagaga Samurai - This double attacker can actually redirect attacks saving statue, mostly there for OTKS KOAKI RATIO: For a while I had 3 Guardians 1 Supplier but I really liked how Supplier plusses my hand, as thats what Vernalizers want. ISHIZU FAIRY RATIO: I ran Kelbek + Keldo for 85% of duels, I wasnt happy in the end with Kelbek handtrap impact this format so I cut the engine... At which point Keldo was switched for Mudora as Mudora has a bit more Attack. - But in side deck this ratios is super valuable, specially if you wanna diversify the endboard, Ishizu fairy techs stomp some matchups. WHAT IF ONE CANT AFFORD 3 FENRIRS? Can you afford 2? 2 Is totally fine. There is no leveled replacement. Other tested stuff > Underperformers (Slightly surprising ones to me ): Rafflesia with Treacherous, (Well Treacherous is a bit bricky, everything floats, you might not reach R4, not to mention this is not R4 only deck + low atk) Gorgonic Guardian (hard gapped by IP masquerena), Aka why Sentry Stone suffered to, also Revival golem was rough competition for Sentry Kelbek (Ishizu handtrap) - its fantastic just some current meta decks like Tearlaments fk it up. It only performed well enough as a common side. Adamancipator Dragite - so by the time you can use this WATER monster your deck is out of rocks XD. What could Konami realistically easily print which would help the deck? If they printed some good level 6 or 8 Earth synchro. Maybe some better earth removal than Diamond dire wolf / Scrap dragon.
Sky Striker (Andriikurnia)

Reviving Destiny HERO Tzolkin through any means. I've played this deck for numerous years and it was super good before MR4 and was barely decent during. At MR5 it hasn't become much better but it's still got its core.

 

Destiny HERO engine to keep true to it's original name. Trickstars engine to enable Ultimaya Tzolkin to be summoned without the long combo of Destiny HERO and Elemental HERO. Branded engine because it is generic and still insanely good. The rest are hand traps and board breakers which weren't able to fit before this so it's a fresh addition to the deck.

deck_excerpt: Troll Masterduel by immediately mill your opponent's entire deck and win by deckout using one of Yugioh's craziest cards - Inferno Tempest!
deck_description:
For this deck to work, you need three conditions to be met:

1. Inferno Tempest in hand.

2. 3000 ATK monster on your opponent's field.

3. Weak monster on your side of the field to run into your opponent's 3000 ATK monster.

With those conditions met, Inferno Tempest can and will banish all of your opponent's monsters in their deck!

The three Necroface in your deck will finish off the rest of the spells and traps in their deck, since the baby will activate 4 times (3 with Necroface, and again when Nyannyan shuffling it back into the deck to banish again).

It's a gimmicky, blind second deck that doesn't always work, but boy is it fun to watch when it pops off!!!

GLHF trolling in Masterduel Duelists! :trollface:

deck_excerpt: Idk why you want to play Summoned Skull but here you go
deck_description: Summoned Skull is one of the most iconic old school cards yet trying to make a deck with it today even for a casual level is a nightmare, adding it to a Archfiend or Red-Eyes deck just makes those already not so good strategies even worse. That's why I made this Magikey variant whose ideal endboard is literally a Summoned Skull plus a The Monarchs Erupt to lock your opponent out of on field monster effects, nothing more nothing less, it might be extremely weak but it has Summoned Skull in our end board which is mission accomplished for me. The combo goes as follows: Activate Magikey World to search for either Magikey Mechmusket - Batosbuster or a level 4 Magikey monster to use as ritual fodder for Batosbuster, use World's second effect to add Magikey Maftea to our hand, activate Maftea to ritual summon Batosbuster, use Batosbuster effect to search for Maginificent Magikey Mafteal, activate Mafteal's effect to summon itself without using our normal summon for the turn, XYZ summon our only extra deck monster in  Magikey Spirit - Vepartu using Batosbuster and Mafteal (Now we don't have extra deck cards allowing us to activate The Monarch's Erupt), activate Vepartu's effect to search for Summoned Skull and finally normal summon said Sumooned Skull. Now for the The Monarch's Erupt part, we obviously play 3 copies of it, plus 3 Foolish Burial Goods to send Pantheism of the Monarchs to the graveyard which we can banish to add Erupt to our hand (If we already have Erupt we send Fullmetalfoes Fusion for a draw 1); we also play some copies of Pot of Desires for extra consistency (Just pray that your copy of Summoned Skull doesn't get banished by it). Lastly, we play Piercing the Darkness to guarantee that Summoned Skull can win in battle, Magikey World also protects Summoned Skull from being destroyed once every turn; then we have triple Solemn Judgment to stops threaths to our backrow like Lightning Storm or Chimeratech Rampage Dragon to name some examples.

deck_excerpt: Fluffal, Frightfur, Edge Imp, Branded, PSY
deck_description:
Main Combos: Mainly, this deck to immediately bring out Frightfur Cruel Whale and double its quick effect by using Cruel Whale as material for making Sabre-Tooth and then using Sabre-Tooth to bring back Cruel Whale. You could also combo Sabre-Tooth with Kraken if there's monsters that can be affected by effects on the field by first fusion summoning Kraken to destroy the monster on the field then use Kraken as fusion material to bring out Sabre-Tooth, and then use Sabre-Tooth's effect to bring back Kraken and then destroy another monster, and if you can, summon Whale. In case you do get Branded fusion or Fallen of Albaz and poly, you can either summon lubellion or Albion to then summon mirrorjade and then get Albion's effect when it's in the grave. Mirrorjade works perfectly as a removal too, and has a lot of attack points.

How to get the fusion monsters: If you get Frightfur patchwork, play it immediately, so then you can easily get 1 chain or scythe (So you can use Whale's other effect to destroy a monster without having to lose any material since the effect makes you destroy one of your own cards) and a poly. Also, if you get Vendor, you can discard it by using either twin twisters or if you have foolish burial goods, you can play that to get a fluffal card or sabres.

deck_excerpt: This deck can put at least 2 interruptions on the field. The deck only uses one combo. The combo can be altered according to hand.
deck_description:
The deck has 2 main starters: Black Metal Dragon and Starliege Seyfert. The combo usually requires 2 discards. The combo requires 2 dragon monsters on the field to do 2 things: Link summon Striker Dragon then Dragunity Knight - Romulus to add both Field spells: Boot Sector Launch & Dragon Ravine. Activate Dragon Ravine by discarding 1 card to send Absorouter Dragon from deck to GY. Add Rokket Tracer to hand using Absorouter's effect, then activate Boot Sector to SS Tracer.
Use Tracer's effect to destroy the field spell special summoning Rokket Recharger from the deck. Link Guardragon Pisty using one of the Rokkets, then link Quadborrel Dragon using the other 2 making sure that both Pisty and Quadborrel point to the same zone and that zone should be empty. Use Pisty's effect to SS 1 dark dragon monster from the banish zone or the GY. Link Dillingerous Dragon using Pisty and the monster you just summoned with Pisty's effect. Activate Quadborrel's effect by discarding 1 card destroying Dillingerous and SS from the GY Tracer and Recharger along with Dillingerous using its own effect. Link Borrelend Dragon using the link monsters and 1 Rokket. Activate Borrelend's effect negating the remaining Rokket on the field and SS the one in the GY. Synchro summon Borreload Savage Dragon and equip Romulus to it. Now, you have a boss monster that can't be destroyed by card effects or battle, can't be targeted by monster effetcs, can attack all monsters your opponent controls and can negate 1 monster's effect on the field while SS another from your GY along with 2 omni negates from Savage Dragon.

The mod adds cards like Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon, Accesscode Talker, Eldlich, Adamancipator, Plunder Patrol and more. Check the Description of this video on YouTube for more info.

Dragonmaid DPE Video & Decklist ┃ MASTER DUEL SEASON 11

We tried to build a deck for how Panik might play modern Yu-gi-oh. Focussing on his use of darkness to promote fear in opponents

into attacking his defences, we use the unchained monsters & strop trap cards to build Sanaphond the Sky Prison (replacing Castle of Dark Illusions)

which slowly builds ATK and Unchained Abomination (replacing King of Yamimakai) to pick off your opponents cards without attacking.

Failing that burn your opponent to death using the firey blazing mirror force.

deck_excerpt: Silly deck that can spam out 5 Time Wizard/Time Wizard of Tomorrow in a single turn.
deck_description:
Today I decided to finally post my favorite joke deck of all time, Time wizard Turbo. Sometimes locals/ranked matches can feel like a drag, it's the same meta decks every time you go, so it just absolutely brightens your day when the Spright player makes Elf to revive Time Wizard, and makes Gigantic to summon one from the deck. Or when the deck uses the Bystial cards to make Beatrice... then pitches Desparado Barrel dragon to add Time Wizard from the deck to hand. This deck has plenty of unexpected plays that look meta untill Time wizard starts flooding the board slowly. The deck's sole purpose is to be a good laugh. Anywho, onto the combos.

 

Firstly we have the spright cards. Time Wizard is a level 2, so they were perfect. Firstly, I should state that Cynet mining is in here to add Draconnet to the hand. Draconnet summons Melffy rabby from the deck, a level 2. So it's a spright extender, most people though, are expecting you to start adding Salamangreat or Mathmech cards. You first make Sprind, who sends TW from the deck to the gy. Then you make Elf who puts that TW onto your board. Then you overlay both link monsters into Gigantic, then detatch a material to summon another TW from the deck. Or, after reviving with Elf, you instead activate Inferno reckless summon to summon 2 TW from your hand/deck/gy for a total of 3 time wizard.

 

Next is bystial. During your opponent's turn, summon Magnamuht, who will let you add Druisworm and summon it. Now, at the start of your turn, you can make Beatrice. Detatch a material from Beatrice to send Desperado barrel dragon from your deck to the gy, it's effect will then trigger adding Time Wizard from your deck to your hand. This can be shortened if you just draw Foolish Burial to send Desperado barrel dragon.

 

Next up is fusion summoning. For this we have Cyberstein who can summon a TWOT before being linked off for sprind/elf.

Frightfur fusion adds polymerization and an edge imp to fuse with. 

Theres instant fusion for an instant TWOT

And lastly you can just draw into magicallized fusion to fuse with a Time wizard that was sent to the gy.

 

Next we have the unreleased cards. Ohime and Arabesque. They protect TW/TWOT from destroying itself so that it can reliably use its effect every turn. These cards aren't out yet, but I added them to the list anyways.

 

Finally we have win condition. The obvious choice here if you scroll down to look at the extra deck for a second, is to burn your opponent to death with Time Wizard of Tomorrow. Jokes aside, it's Selene into Accesscode since Time Wizard is a spellcaster. And theres also Beatrice/Gigantic into Zeus to give you a clear shot at game if your opponent thought your deck had no win con and was goofing slacking to see what your deck could do. I decided on these two though because Zeus wipes things like Time wizard does so it fit with the theme, and you need Time wizard to enable Selene to go into Accesscode. I had to make sure Time Wizard was a piece of every win con.

 

Well thats all on this deck. Sadly, it's way over priced for a joke deck, so if you happen to have the pricy cards from your tournament decks, then I definately reccomend you buy the few cheap cards you need to make the deck so you can spice up the locals next time you go. There's just one thing you meed to remember though, this is a coin flip based deck, so remember the chant "Tails never fails!" To increace your odds of calling the flip from 50% to 80%. As alwayse, hope you enjoy!

This deck has a few too many spells for sanity's sake.

Feedback is always welcome.

Konami needs to retrain this archetype.

Feedback is always welcome.

deck_excerpt: Hyper Consistent Athena OTK Deck, only needs 1 of them too.
deck_description:
This deck is a hyper consistent FTK Athena Deck. The best part of this deck, it doesn't require you to draw into an Athena at all (though if you do there's an easier OTK as well)

turn 1
normal summon agent of mystery - earth
give yourself either neptune or venus depending on what's not in your hand, sacred waters can also give you whatever you might be missing, and similarly so can small world. Main banish targets for small world are: light to light, ixchel or stardestroyer, ixchel to light, stardestroyer,

opening hand(s) to FTK:
some variant of:
earth
neptune/venus (earth can give one, so you only need the other)

darklord contact and monster reborn make it easier for 1 athena OTK

anyways, main combo for 1 athena OTK:
earth, give what's missing
neptune, summon venus
venus, summon all 3 orbs (cost 1.5k hp)
use 2 of the orbs to make protector of the agents moon
use moon, send to the gy hyperion
use hyperion banish neptune
neptune gives the santuary in the sky
place sanctuary in the sky
use moon and one of the orbs for condemned darklord
give yourself superbia to the hand
then link 3 off venus, into pars
dump superbia for athena
use earth and hyperion who should still be on the board to summon your synchro monster
use synchro to foolish and copy destruction venus.
before foolishing you should get a monster effect from pars this allows you to banish a mystic shining ball and summon athena
now, use hyperions copied effect to recycle the 3 mystic shining balls and summon them to the field
now, use monsters in the extra deck (leave condemned alone though) to loop through roughly 3k of the enemies HP till all of your balls are returned to the extra deck. 
Now, if you have darklord contact or monster reborn you can use this in place of Athena's skill. Revive superbia, revive agent of creation venus. (1.2k damage to the enemy)
revive the mystic shining balls and craft condemned darklords. This will loop through about another 2k-3k HP. 
continue to use superbia, condemned, and the other cards to summon more fairys from the extra deck until you kill

 

Truthfully, you can remove the l3 trickstar and the first darklord for 2 more fairy l2 monsters, but you shouldn't have any issues burning the enemy to death anyways.

 

Second combo:
hand needed:
venus
neptune/the sanctuary in the sky/sacred waters
athena

neptune to summon venus, summon 3 orbs
if you had to use neptune, make moon and dump hyperion and use his effect to summon himself and get the sanctuary in the sky
if you have the sanctuary in the sky or sacred waters, ignore that step and just activate sanctuary in the sky
use moon if you made him hyperion to make condemned darklord and give yourself superbia, dump athena, if you had the sanctuary in the sky you can just use 2 of the orbs, skip moon, and make condemned
then, use venus and condemned to make l3 pars, make sure that the sanctuary in the sky is on the field
dump superbia for athena
summon link spider off your remaining orb, and use pars to summon athena 1
then kill pars, summon superbia, who will summon athena
then link off athena 1 and superbia
and repeatedly kill your linked off monster with athena 1 or 2 revolving order and revive superbia and athena from the gy.

Hi guys,

Basically, I designed the Main deck and the Extra deck for a friend who start and learn the game. In order to give a budget decklist, I decided to create a Side deck based on many hand traps/floodgates reachable through 2022's structure decks.

Some thoughts

  • I decided not to include Fluffal package (I don't have it ATM). To have some access to Polymerization, I added King of the Swamp.

However (because I had one free spot and I would stay on a 40-card decklist), I added Heritage of the Light as a niche draw card (since you play a lot of fusion)

 

Some Improvements

  • To add some extra draw power in the deck => Allure of Darkness x2-3
  • Fluffal package if you want some alternative to search Polymerization
  • If you have some extra budget to build the deck, Super Polymerization and its meta targets (Starving Venom, ...)

Feel free to give your feedback and ideas in the comment to improve this list :)

Thanks all!

deck_excerpt: Toon deck for SPIRIT CALLER 2006 on the 3DS
deck_description:
Yu-Gi-Oh! GX SPIRIT CALLER has a limited selection of cards, so building any archetype outside of the main cast for Season 1 is...hard. I built a functional Toon themed deck for fun.

Try and play Vengeful Bog Spirit  as soon as possible, it'll put the same limit on your opponent as your Toon monsters on you. You have SIX deck searchers + 3 Toon Worlds, so 25% of your deck is getting Toon World on the field; OG toon monsters are easier to special summon from higher levels, and opponents don't have a defence against direct attacks. Stall out your opponent + buff your life points with Spell Absorption (computer A.I. will avoid attacking Fiend's Sanctuary unless they become cornered, or will OTK you).

Side deck: If you unlocked Monster Reborn (from Atticus), replace Premature Burial. If you don't care for building your Life Points up, swap out some Spell cards for Ceasefire, and keep Jar of Greed if you want to draw more of your deck.

Yu-Gi-Oh! GX SPIRIT CALLER has a limited selection of cards, so building any archetype outside of the main cast for Season 1 is...hard. I can't remember where I found this, but it is from a user named Inomaru89, it is possibly the meta deck for the game.

This is a great synergy deck, you can rapidly summon Red-Eyes Black Dragon using Masked Dragon, into Black Dragon's Chick, milling your deck to draw strong cards, or fill your graveyard with dragons to power Red-Eyes Darkness Dragon. Alternative you can go straight into a Horus beatdown deck with strong monsters. This deck isn't flawless, but it rarely bricks, the only times it lost was because the opponent drew better.

Side Deck: If you acquired Harpie's Feather Duster  (from Blair)/Monster Reborn (from Atticus), replace Heavy Storm, or Premature Burial.

Before anything, we can all agree that Witchcrafter is not a super-powerful deck, right? okay. 

Witchrafters usually die in any match-up against Tear if they go second, so this is a hard-go first deck that revolves around setting up floodgates and summoning Vice-Madame as fast as humanly possible to be able to use her effects as much as possible to create fields.

deck_excerpt: Tearlament Ishizu, my 4 months Experiment, STAY STRONG
deck_description:
Welcome everyone, this is your friendly neighbor Lohamora ( you expected spiderman )

time to discover the true power of tier 0 format, cuz Magnificent Mavens has arrived.

 

time to talk about strategies in the deck, you might hear or even see some of them, but the chance of not knowing some of them are high.

 Main deck 

- the Bystial Magnamhut: this card doesn't only search any dragon monsters from the deck, it can also add dragon monsters from the graveyard so doesn't matter if you milled the Druidwurm or not you can still add him back, you can also add any extra deck monster from graveyard to the deck, people in OCG always played these 3 as hand traps, and OP monsters to break boards, but it might become unhealthy if you play more than 4 the Bystial monsters.

* There is also a new Bystial coming in Photon Hydra Nova, called the Bystial Baldrake, take look at this card if you had time, it's OP

 

- the Keldo the Sacred Protector: this card is the best of all Ishizu cards, but what exactly should I add to it, well the answer is always been clear, you will add Agido the ancient sentinel, cuz you know for sure you're going to mill cards (for example, you used Keldo to discard Kelbek the ancient Vanguard) so you can use Agido to special summon one of those Ishizu cards you milled and make an easy Rank 4 monster, also if you milled both of your Tearlament Sullieks then special summoned Kitkallos, you can use Mudora or Keldo to shuffle the traps, then add trap with Kitkallos 

 

 

- Tearlament Reinoheart: in the Tearlament Danger deck it is a must to play 3 copies of this card, cuz it's a good starter, but here two copies are what you need, Ishizu cards fixed the milling problem deck had, it even made it better, so in this deck, you always get to mill a Tearlament monster, there is no way you won't mill, you have at least maximum 20 cards mills in 1 turn with this deck.

- Diviner of the Herald: with this card, you can mill any Ishizu cards like Agido or Kelbek to mill 5 cards or Mudora or Keldo, in case you've already milled all your Tearlament monsters, now why some people calling Diviner a waste of space in the extra deck, well they play Baronne with Elder entity N'tess but you really don't need to play Elder while you have already cards in your deck does the same thing ( next note ), also deck has 6 normal summons with Diviner, don't ever think you have too many normal summonses in the deck, cuz 6 isn't a high number.

- Primeval Planet Perlereino with Mudora or Keldo: field spell says if a Tearlament monster shuffled back into the deck or extra deck, you can target one card on the field and destroy it, so why do you need to play Elder while you have the same mechanic in your deck, which is more consistent then Elder, conclusion 2 copies of Diviner of the Herald isn't waste of space, but you have 2 choose 3 copies of the Merrli with 1 Diviner or 2 copies of both the Merrli and Diviner, both do the same thing but I would rather pick the first one.

- Herald of orange light: the chance of drawing this card with one fairy is 80% but it gets nasty if you discard Agido or Kelbek with it, also it's a level 2 tuner so you can make Baronne with this card and Rulkallos 

- Instant fusion: the best way to use this card, is to add Reinoheart after you summoned Kitkallos then you can special Reinoheart and send Kitkallos to Graveyard to draw more cards.

Extra deck

- Tearlament Kaleido-heart: summoning this monster in turn 0 without having Tearlament Sulliek or Baronne isn't a good idea, but if you already had Baronne like by summoning with Diviner, you use Barrone to pop Kaleido-heart then you can trigger its effect and send one more Tearlament.

- Number 41: Bagooska: my Yugioh experiments showed me, decks that play a dimensional shifter really die to Number 41, and please if you had a way to summon Bagooska under the shifter, please do it even if the cost seems heavy, cuz decks play shifter really die to Number 41, I managed to make Bagooska like 6 times from 10 times I was under the shifter, the last thing you can also summon Bagooska when you bricked to steal some time, hoping for a good top deck.

-I:P Masquerena: this card is really broken you only need 2 none-link monsters to make it, and use its effect to link summon Spright Sprind and mill the Merrli then go for fusion summoning Kitkallos and start playing in your opponent's turn.

- Borreload Dragon: when you have the game, but cuz of high attack monster you can't win, or cuz of an unkillable monster like Mekk-knight Avramax, this is the best card to steal your opponent's monster, by placing the monster in the link zone this card points too ( no targetting ) and your opponent can't respond to this card activation, conclusion this card is 100% worthy to play.

-AA-Arsenal Zeus: I've seen TCG players rarely summon Zeus, but this card is broken to out the boards, and let me tell you, Tearlament loves to be sent to the graveyard by card effects, but how we usually summon this card, when by using number 41 most likely.

Side deck:
going second:

Lava golem: as you saw this deck only has 6 normal summons, and 70% of the time you don't have a normal summons, so lava golem is here to out the boards.

Ghost reaper: this card is a game-ender in the mirror match and since the deck is popular among a lot of people, and the main heart of the deck is Kitkallos, you can easily get rid of it, and they lose the game, but if they get lucky to mill, Tearlament Cryme they can recycle it back, and start play again, there is no way to win when your opponent ghost reapers you in the mirror match ( the only exception explained above ), I lost some games in mirror matches because of this card, so OP in the mirror match.

Kashtira Fenrir: the best second-going card in the world, out for the continue trap cards ( floodgates ), or banishing monsters face down to bother your opponent lul, you can add a second copy of Fenrir even by using itself, now where is Aussa the earth charmer, well reviving back Fenrir is the only use for Aussa, I leave you to decide between Aussa and I:P Masquerena, I would play Maquerena instead of Aussa.

Lightning storm with galaxy cyclone: yes back-row decks are painful, especially Runick, which right now is the most hated deck along with Floowandereeze and of course with dear Mystic mine, guess some People like Fewer IQ decks.

Evenly matched: none of the Tearlament decks can make Omni negate except for the Baronne part, so this card is so good right now.

 First going ( this deck is already strong by going first, but we might need some boost )

Triple tactic talents: see your opponent hand, take control of a painful monster your opponent controls, and draw 2 cards, usually, I choose the first one, if I know I can play if my opponent doesn't have one more interruption, but the choice always is yours.

Kashtira Fenrir: yes this card is even good when you go First, adding one more interruption is always excepted

Tearlament Cryme: to deal with cards like Dark ruler or evenly matched, also to recycle back Kitkallos if she got banished somehow.

Last notes:
is this deck dies to floodgates? depends if they have Primeval Planet Perlereino with Mudora or Keldo and one Tearlament monster in Graveyard, they can out the Floodgates.

is this deck dies to the dark ruler? 80% the answer is not, they have so many ways to mill cards, even in your own turn, so don't play Dark ruler in the main deck, better play in the side deck, now why I don't have Dark ruler in side deck, this deck already strong to deal with the board going first or Second in game 1.

what is the right time, to use Our Bystials to banish Tearlament monsters? before they summon Kitkallos, never allow them to summon Kitkallos, never!!

if I had 2 Tearlament monsters in the graveyard to trigger their effects, should I use both? yes, if your opponent had a Bystials, they can banish one of them, and you lost your chance for fusion summoning.
 
the End

hope I could help you somehow, this was my 4 monthly experiment with this deck on online games, believe me, online games are harder than real-world games, I swear some of these online players are smarter than real-world YuGiOh players but don't have enough money.

Till next time we're going to discover Sky striker deck Post Mama ( cringe name lul ) for the new format. Cya

deck_excerpt: When Red is the new Green
deck_description:
Updated*

Replaced some cards to increase efficiency. No longer within the 40-card threshold as well.

Introduction:

The ultimate chain for days deck

Don't be alarmed by the so many different traps. They are meant to be there.

This expert deck requires the utmost precision in decision-making at every step.

Some are pretty self-explanatory, so I'm not going to discuss them.

Note: There are very few 3x copies in this deck. I think 3x copies are just wasting potential for a creative deck. I would rather see a deck having more outcomes than a deck that wins games.

Discussions

Main:

With the new Big Welcome Labrynth, the need for 3 x Welcome Labrynth is a waste. Welcome Labrynth is the first Labrynth trap you search for and can be recycled at almost every turn. I recommend a maximum of 2 copies.

Big Welcome Labrynth now acts as an opening, support, as well as a Compulsory Evacuation Device. Just an explanation if you wondered why there is no Compulsory Evacuation Device in this deck.

I think 3x or 2x Arianna the Labrynth Servant is fine. While it is the deck's search engine, after playing with so many constraints, I do not think Arianna the Labrynth Servant on your hand will make so much of a difference.

Labrynth Chandraglier, Labrynth Stovie Torbie, Labrynth Cooclock - They are pretty good if you use them well. 2x Labrynth Stovie Torbie only as the field will get jammed.

Labrynth Barrage - I think it is a frustrating piece of card that often sits there and does nothing useful. When you can't use it, it becomes a brick, and when you can use it, it often results in overkill. Not recommended.

1x Lady Labrynth of the Silver Castle, 1x Lovely Labrynth of the Silver Castle - I think 1 each is enough. If it gets banished, it is painful, but if you bricked, it's just pain. Recommend at most 2x Lady Labrynth of the Silver Castle Update: Added +1 Lady Labrynth of the Silver Castle as it is really painful if it gets banished.

Labrynth Set-Up - If you spam your traps, maybe, and that is only when the traps are very powerful and not enough to come by. In this case, there is no such power spike and limitation. I don't think it's worth placing it in unless you are playing a battle royale that lasts very long.

Miscellaneous:

Note: Just swap them if you don't like them

Vivid Tail - Very odd card taste but can be useful in this deck especially when many of Labrynth's effects require a monster to leave the field.

Weight Measuring - A non-destructive single-use floodgate

Fiend Griefing - In addition to sending cards to the grave as an effect, you get to shuffle GY things

Added: Waking the Dragon - If you get feathered, and you have a Lady Labrynth of the Silver Castle and an activatable trap, activate the trap and chain Lady Labrynth of the Silver Castle effect on top, set Waking the Dragon, and now you have a free ultimate falcon.

Added: Anti-Spell Fragrance - If they can't beat you with monsters, they will attempt to beat you with spells. Slow down the spell flank. You can search the field via Labrynth Chandraglier, Labrynth Stovie Torbie.

Added: 2x Infinite Impermanence as someone complained about efficiency.

Added: Dogmatika Punishment

Side deck:

I use the side deck to show potential cards that can be used.

Moved: Starlight Road - Just in case.

Moved: Paleozoic Dinomischus - Discards as an effect, can be useful in situations

Moved: Scrap-Iron Scarecrow  - Repeatable trap and can be searched by Labrynth Archfiend 

Moved: Harpie's Feather Duster

Genta, Gateman of Dark World - Many use cases. Funny that I use it in decks other than a dark world deck.

Ghost Belle & Haunted Mansion - To avoid painful card banishes. 

The Fabled Cerburrel - Fabled archetype. Pairs well but can be redundant.

Accumulated Fortune - So many chains.

Diabolica, Dragon Fiend Commander - Can be useful in certain situations

deck_description:
Infinitrack Brutal Dozer is an awesome card, it´s so awsome that, to some people, they won't call this deck an Earth Machine deck, they will call a Dozer control deck.

What archetypes do we have in this deck:

1 We have the trains (choo choo), more know as the lvl 10 otk
